NI urgently needs a DA Commissioner as England and Wales has @CommissionerDA and a solid strategy on tackling violence against women and girls. Granting bail to a man who threatened to kill a woman, and acted upon it, and releasing back into the community is extremely dangerous.

The system in every part of the UK is flawed in favour of perpetrators, while victims are left to fend for themselves. The judge acknowledged Howe is a risk to half the population yet proceeded to set a low bail so as not to overburden the prison service. Victims must come first.

The judge claimed Howe was 'a danger to women', citing 'this is the worst case I have come across in 22 years on the bench.' However, despite initially insisting bail be set by High Court, Judge Hamill later granted bail of £500, due to quarantine rules in prison.

This affects the sentence which can be passed down for the crime. Among Howe's convictions was 'wounding', which in the lower court carries a maximum sentence of 1 year. It is up to 7 years in Crown Court.

At a glance, the perpetrator - David Howe - was convicted of threatening his former partner with a knife. He also stabbed her three times in the head. Because the PPS didn't take the case seriously, the case was heard at the Magistrates' Court, rather than at Crown Court.

There are so many more amazing bands, whose hits are too numerous to mention, but check out Die Ärtzte, Die Toten Hosen, Nena (she had more than just the hit that made her name on this side of the pond) and of course the institution that is Schlager! Viel Spass! https://t.co/qbvWyTXMbO

BBC called him 'Germany's answer to Bruce Springsteen' but Ruhrpotters call them their own. Herbert Groenemeyer is probably the most famous German musician of all time. I'm biased but I'd say his 'must hear' hit is a love song is to his home city, Bochum. https://t.co/N0JBCr4CxX

Wir sind Helden (We are Heroes) were huge in their day and their album Von Hier an Blind, (Walking Blind), is a fab.  Gekommen um zu bleiben, (Here to Stay) is a belter yet sadly the band decided to take an indefinite hiatus in 2012. I'm not bitter. https://t.co/MExo7rHQz8

Let it never be said that Germans can't take a joke. (H.P. Baxxter himself is said to be laughing all the way to the bank with a reported net worth of $50million.) Supermarket chain Edeka teamed up with the hitmaker to advertise their best budget buys: https://t.co/HXzYOBWqVB

Techno have had its day in the late 90s in the UK, not so in Germany.  H.P. Baxxter, better known as Scooter, is one of the genre's shining lights releasing tunes such as 'How much is the fish?' to the delight of the masses: https://t.co/gbQoT6DmcG

And because I love them so much you can have this bonus track, which is more recent, and is a dig at the swell in support for the AfD - Baby, du driftest nach rechts (Baby, you're drifting to the Right)  https://t.co/I0MPy84NyU

Fettes Brot are a hip hop act who formed in Hamburg in the 90s who regularly use their music to analyse social and political issues happening at home and abroad. An Tagen Wie Diesen (On Days Like These) is a great example of this.https://t.co/UVdpYcuLwD

Germany is one of the biggest music markets in the world to break but once a band has cracked it German fans are very loyal.  This may be one of the reasons why Depeche Mode are as popular there now as when they first burst onto the scene.(See also Roxette & Ace of Base.)

Germans LOVE abbreviations, most wonderfully demonstrated in this track, made famous by one of Germany's biggest hip hop groups, Die Fantastischen Vier (or Fanta4 if you're one of the cool kids): https://t.co/WxtvbpZjHH

@ShafLdn Alright, I have massively fallen down a rabbit hole on this one and have a renewed 'fernweh' to go back to Germany, whose language is somewhat cruelly underrated but in my opinion, one of the greatest in the world.  For this defence I present the following cracker tunes:

@ShafLdn No going back.  You'll love it.  I'll send you some of my faves later on.  Bear in mind I lived there 15 years ago and my knowledge of what is happening on the music scene now is very limited.  BUT it means I'm going to send you some classics!

@ShafLdn I am sort of fluent but find that fluency depletes the less you actively use a language.  I went through a period where most of my work involved speaking German and it felt quite effortless but, sadly, I don't really dream in German anymore.  It's a gorgeous language though.
